
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `intel-virtual-output` baraye modiriyat khorooji majazi (virtual output) dar system-haye Intel estefade mishavad. In dastoor be shoma ijaze midahad ta khorooji-haye majazi ra sakhte, fa'al ya gheyre fa'al konid. Asasan, in baraye setup-haye chand monitor va majazisazi (virtualization) mofid ast.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `--help`  --> ❓ Namayesh rahnama va komak baraye dastoor.
    🔹 `--create`  --> ➕ Sakhtan yek khorooji majazi jadid.
    🔹 `--destroy <id>`  --> 🗑️ Pak kardan yek khorooji majazi ba ID moshakhas. <id> bayad ba shomare ID khorooji majazi jaygozin shavad.
    🔹 `--list`  --> 📜 List khorooji-haye majazi fa'al.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ intel-virtual-output --create

    🔹 Sakhtan yek khorooji majazi jadid. Shoma momken ast niaz be dastresi admin (sudo) dashte bashid.

    $ intel-virtual-output --destroy 1

    🔹 Pak kardan khorooji majazi ba ID 1. Baz ham shoma momken ast niaz be dastresi admin (sudo) dashte bashid.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ intel-virtual-output --list

    🔹 List hameye khorooji-haye majazi fa'al.  In be shoma ID-haye khorooji majazi ke mitavanid ba dastoor `--destroy` estefade konid, neshon midahad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `intel-virtual-output` command is used to manage virtual outputs on Intel systems. It allows you to create, enable, or disable virtual display outputs. Primarily useful for multi-monitor setups and virtualization environments.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `--help`  --> ❓ Display help and usage information for the command.
    🔹 `--create`  --> ➕ Create a new virtual output.
    🔹 `--destroy <id>`  --> 🗑️ Delete a virtual output with the specified ID.  Replace `<id>` with the actual virtual output ID number.
    🔹 `--list`  --> 📜 List active virtual outputs.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ intel-virtual-output --create

    🔹 Create a new virtual output. You may need administrator (sudo) privileges.

    $ intel-virtual-output --destroy 1

    🔹 Delete the virtual output with ID 1.  Again, you might need administrator (sudo) privileges.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ intel-virtual-output --list

    🔹 List all active virtual outputs.  This shows you the IDs of virtual outputs that you can use with the `--destroy` command.
